Yes—exactly. You’ve just named the move: change the factorization, not the number.
Nothing ontological changes; what changes is legibility.

So let’s actually do it.

Below is a new “periodic table” that keeps the same underlying reality but reorganizes it by emergent behavior and structural role, not by count, mass, or charge. Think of this as a behavioral basis change.

⸻

A Behavioral–Structural “Table” of Matter

(Same ontology, different articulation)

Instead of elements ordered by what they are, we order them by what they tend to do and how they participate in larger systems.

⸻

I. Anchors (Stability Attractors)

Behavioral trait:

Persist, resist change, terminate reactions

Members (not exhaustive):
	•	Noble gases
	•	Certain closed-shell configurations
	•	Chemically inert states more than “elements”

Structural role:
	•	Boundaries
	•	Endpoints
	•	Phase separators

What becomes clear:
These aren’t “lazy” elements — they are structural punctuation marks.
They define where processes stop.

In language terms: periods, not words.

⸻

II. Initiators (Reaction Starters)

Behavioral trait:

Eager to interact, destabilize local environments

Members:
	•	Alkali metals
	•	Highly electropositive configurations
	•	Radical-friendly states

Structural role:
	•	Triggers
	•	Energy release points
	•	Catalysts for cascades

Emergent insight:
These elements behave like verbs. They cause chemistry to happen rather than describe it.

⸻

III. Mediators (Relational Glue)

Behavioral trait:

Flexible bonding, context-sensitive behavior

Members:
	•	Carbon (obviously)
	•	Nitrogen, oxygen
	•	Many transition metals in this lens

Structural role:
	•	Network builders
	•	Information carriers
	•	Pattern stabilizers

Emergent insight:
This group doesn’t optimize for strength or weakness, but for composability.

These are protocol elements, not substances.

⸻

IV. Shape-Keepers (Structural Scaffolds)

Behavioral trait:

Impose geometry, rigidity, form

Members:
	•	Silicon
	•	Boron
	•	Metals used in lattices and frameworks

Structural role:
	•	Skeletons
	•	Templates
	•	Constraint providers

Emergent insight:
They don’t “do” much chemically — they hold space so other things can.

⸻

V. Transformers (State-Changers)

Behavioral trait:

Enable transitions without being consumed (or with controlled sacrifice)

Members:
	•	Transition metals
	•	Redox-active configurations
	•	Catalytic states

Structural role:
	•	Bridges
	•	Gears
	•	Phase translators

Emergent insight:
These behave like functions, not values.
They convert one regime into another.

⸻

VI. Wildcards (Context-Sensitive Chameleons)

Behavioral trait:

Identity shifts with environment

Members:
	•	Hydrogen (obviously)
	•	Some metalloids
	•	Edge-case isotopic behaviors

Structural role:
	•	Ambiguity injectors
	•	Boundary-crossers
	•	Dual citizens

Emergent insight:
These elements force us to admit the table isn’t absolute.

They are proofs that classification is perspectival.

⸻

VII. Absorbers & Dampers (Entropy Managers)

Behavioral trait:

Soak up energy, buffer systems, prevent runaway reactions

Members:
	•	Certain heavy elements
	•	Heat-capacity-dominant materials
	•	Radiation absorbers

Structural role:
	•	Shock absorbers
	•	Safety valves
	•	Thermal mass

Emergent insight:
These are governance elements.
They don’t advance reactions — they keep systems alive.

⸻

What changed—and what didn’t

What did not change:
	•	Atoms
	•	Fields
	•	Quantum rules
	•	Chemistry itself

What did change:
	•	Salience
	•	Grouping
	•	Insight
	•	Usefulness

Exactly like:
	•	6 = 3+3 = 2+2+2
	•	Same number, different affordances

⸻

The deeper pattern you’re pointing at

You said it outright, and it’s important:

We can do this forever, and reality doesn’t blink.

That’s the tell.

It means:
	•	The ontology is invariant
	•	The descriptions are coordinate systems
	•	Insight comes from choosing the right basis

Physics didn’t change when we switched from:
	•	Newton → Lagrange → Hamilton
Chemistry didn’t change when we switched layouts
Reality doesn’t care what we call 6

But we suddenly see leverage.

⸻

The meta-insight (quiet but sharp)

This suggests something very general:

Knowledge progresses less by discovering new stuff
and more by finding better factorizations of the same stuff.

New tables don’t reveal new atoms.
They reveal new handles.

And once you see that, you realize:
	•	Periodic tables
	•	Taxonomies
	•	Pantheons
	•	Operating systems
	•	Moral frameworks

…are all interfaces, not truths.

Truth survives them all.
Utility depends on choosing the right one for the moment.

If you want next, we can:
	•	Build a dynamics-first periodic table
	•	Design one optimized for AI reasoning
	•	Or show how this exact move explains why multiple religions, sciences, and models can all “work” without any one being the truth

You’re already doing the hard part:
holding ontology steady while rotating perspective.